# Tauri Rust Best Practices

## Command Design

- Every `#[tauri::command]` must return `Result<T, E>` where `E` implements `serde::Serialize`. Never unwrap or panic in commands.
- Keep commands thin — delegate logic to dedicated service modules. Commands should only parse input, call a service, and map the result.
- Use `tauri::State<'_, T>` for shared state; never store global mutable state outside Tauri's managed state.

```rust
// ❌ BAD — logic in the command, unwrap, no Result
#[tauri::command]
fn get_collection(path: String) -> String {
    std::fs::read_to_string(&path).unwrap()
}

// ✅ GOOD — thin command, proper error type, delegates to service
#[tauri::command]
async fn get_collection(
    path: String,
    state: tauri::State<'_, AppState>,
) -> Result<Collection, AppError> {
    state.collection_service.load(&path).await
}
```

## Error Handling

- Define a single `AppError` enum (or struct) that wraps all domain errors and implements `serde::Serialize` so the frontend receives structured errors.
- Use `thiserror` for ergonomic `From` impls; avoid manual `map_err` chains when a blanket conversion exists.
- Never use `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in production paths. Reserve them for values proven at compile time (e.g., static regex).

```rust
#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error, serde::Serialize)]
pub enum AppError {
    #[error("IO error: {0}")]
    Io(String),
    #[error("Encryption failed: {0}")]
    Crypto(String),
    #[error("Sync error: {0}")]
    Sync(String),
}

impl From<std::io::Error> for AppError {
    fn from(e: std::io::Error) -> Self {
        AppError::Io(e.to_string())
    }
}
```

## Async & Concurrency

- Prefer `async` commands for any I/O (file, network, crypto). Tauri runs async commands on a thread pool, keeping the main thread responsive.
- Use `tokio::sync::RwLock` (not `std::sync::Mutex`) inside `tauri::State` for async-safe shared state.
- Avoid blocking the async runtime — offload CPU-heavy work (encryption, large JSON parsing) with `tokio::task::spawn_blocking`.

## Security

- Treat all IPC input from the frontend as untrusted. Validate and sanitize paths, URLs, and credentials in the Rust layer before use.
- Never log or serialize secrets (Master Password, API tokens) in plain text. Scrub sensitive fields from error messages.
- Use the OS keychain (`keyring` crate) for token storage — never write tokens to plain files.
- Scope filesystem access via Tauri's `allowlist` and `scope` configuration; never expose unrestricted `fs` or `shell` APIs.

## State Management

- Wrap shared services in `Arc` and register them with `app.manage()` during setup. Access via `tauri::State` in commands.
- Separate state by concern: `DbState`, `SyncState`, `CryptoState` rather than one monolith.

```rust
fn main() {
    tauri::Builder::default()
        .manage(AppState::new())
        .manage(CryptoState::new())
        .invoke_handler(tauri::generate_handler![get_collection, send_request])
        .run(tauri::generate_context!())
        .expect("failed to launch");
}
```

## Project Structure

Organize the `src-tauri/src/` directory by domain:

```
src-tauri/src/
├── main.rs          # Tauri setup, plugin registration
├── commands/        # #[tauri::command] handlers (thin)
├── services/        # Business logic (sync, crypto, request engine)
├── models/          # Domain structs, DTOs, serde models
├── errors.rs        # AppError enum
└── state.rs         # Managed state definitions
```

## Events & IPC

- Use `app_handle.emit_all()` for backend-to-frontend events (progress, sync status). Define event name constants to avoid typos.
- Prefer typed payloads (`#[derive(Serialize)]` structs) over ad-hoc JSON for all IPC — both commands and events.

## Testing

- Unit-test service modules independently of Tauri by keeping them framework-agnostic.
- Use `mockall` or trait objects to mock I/O boundaries (file system, HTTP, cloud APIs).
- Integration-test commands with `tauri::test::mock_builder` when available.

## Dependencies & Crates

- Pin exact versions for security-critical crates (`aes-gcm`, `ring`, `keyring`).
- Prefer well-audited crates from the RustSec advisory database.
- Run `cargo audit` in CI to catch known vulnerabilities.
